On an incline with slope angle $\alpha$ there lies a cylinder with mass $M$, its axis being horizontal. A small block with mass $m$ is placed inside it. The coefficient of friction between the block and the cylinder is $\mu$; the incline is nonslippery. What is the maximum slope angle $\alpha$ for the cylinder to stay at rest? The block is much smaller than the radius of the cylinder.
\begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width = 0.4\textwidth]{block_in_block_kalda.jpg}
    \end{center}

solution:
There are only 3 forces on this rod. Thus, if we consider torque about the intersection point of two of them, the third must intersect as well, for there to be 0 net torque. Now, we have reduced it to a geometry problem. See the following diagram:
    \begin{center}
        \includegraphics[width=6cm]{rod_bowl.png}
    \end{center}
    We can calculate the length $BD$ in two ways.
    \begin{align*}
        BD &= BC - DC = 2R\cos \theta - R,\\
        BD &= AB \tan \theta = 2R \sin \theta \tan \theta.
    \end{align*}
    Thus, equating the two and simplifying, we get
    $$2\cos \theta - 1 = 2\frac{\sin^2\theta}{\cos \theta}.$$
    This gives us the quadratic
    $$4\cos^2 \theta - \cos \theta - 2 = 0,$$
    so solving we get $\theta \approx 32.5^\circ$.

